3nd.title: Logarithm
3nd.text:
The logarithm of a number is the length of that number, for a certain specific (and empirically very useful) notion of "length." For example, the logarithm of 10 is 1, the logarithm of 100 is 2, the logarithm of 1000 is 3, and the logarithm of 10,000 is 4. "Logarithm" is commonly abbreviated "log." The logs of 103 and 981 are both between 2 and 3, with the log of 103 being very close to 2 and the log of 981 being very close to 3.

The specific notion of length captured by logarithms is that the logarithm of $x$ is the answer to the question "how many times do we have to multiply 1 by 10 to get $x$?" Thus, the logarithm of 10 is 1, the logarithm of 1,000,000 is 6, and so on. To find the logarithm of numbers that are not a [exponential_power power] of 10, we use the notion of [fractional_exponent fractional exponentiation]: Multiplying ten "half a time" means multiplying by $\sqrt{10}$, because if you multiply $x$ by $\sqrt{10}$ twice, then you get $10x.$ Thus, the logarithm of 316 is roughly 2.5, because 316 is roughly $10 \cdot 10 \cdot \sqrt{10}.$ We can use this method to figure out how many multiples of 10 are in a number, which is the logarithm (base 10) of that number. This means that, in the sense that 103 is "barely using three digits" and 981 is "using almost all of three digits," 361 is "using almost exactly two and a half digits." For more on this interpretation of logarithms, and why it is 316 rather than 500 that can most naturally be seen as "using 2.5 digits," see the page on [logarithm_as_generalized_length logarithms as generalized lengths].

There are actually multiple different logarithm functions, depending on what [number_base base] is used to represent numbers. In common notation, the length of a number goes up by one every time the number is multiplied by ten: "300" is one digit longer than "30" is one digit longer that "3", and so on. The [common_logarithm common (base ten) logarithm] describes the length of a number written in common notation. We can alternatively use a [log_base_2 base 2 logarithm] that goes up by one every time the number is multiplied by two. According to base two logarithms, "8" is one unit longer than "4" is one unit longer than "2", and so on. (In other words, the base two logarithm is measuring the length of a number represented using [binary_notation binary notation].) For every number, there is a logarithm function with that base, which gives the "length" of numbers represented in that base.

Given a number $b$, $\log_b$ (pronounced "log base b") is a [3jy function] that takes a number as input and produces a number as output. $\log_b(x)$ is defined to be the answer to the question "how many times do you have to multiply 1 by $b$ to get $x$?" Formally, $\log_b(x)$ is defined to be the number $y$ such that $b^y = x.$ %%%knows-requisite([1r6]): ($y$ is unique if by "number" we mean [real_number $\mathbb R$], but may not be unique if by "number" we mean [complex_number $\mathbb C$]. See the page on [complex_logarithm complex logarithms] for details.)
%%%

Logarithms are an important and recurring concept in many fields, including mathematics, physics, engineering, computer science, cognitive science, and artificial intelligence.

Perhaps the most important use for logarithms is that they give us a tool for measuring information. If I want to single out one object from a collection of 100 objects to you, how many digits do I need to transmit? Measuring information content is the cornerstone of [information_theory information theory]. It has important applications to physics, where our statistical models of what a physical system is going to do next depend on the amount of information in the system that we're missing; for more on this, see the page on [physical_entropy physical entropy]. It also has important applications to probability theory, where the information in an observation is proportional to the strength of evidence it carries; for more on this, see the page on [bayesian_evidence Bayesian evidence].

In mathematics, the most natural logarithmic base is [mathematics_e $e$], and the log base $e$ of $x$ is written $\ln(x)$, pronounced "[natural_logarithm natural log] of x." The natural logarithm of a number gives one notion of the "intrinsic length" of a number, a concept that proves useful when reasoning about other properties of that number. For example, the quantity of prime numbers smaller than $x$ is approximately $\frac{x}{\ln(x)},$ this is the [prime_number_theorem prime number theorem].

Other applications of logarithms include:
[fixme: Make a page on Kolmolgorov complexity that's worth greenlinking from here.]

1. The logarithm is the inverse of the [exponential_function exponential function]. Thus, logarithms give us tools for analyzing anything that grows exponentially. If a population of bacteria grows exponentially, then logarithms can be used to answer questions about how long it will take the population to reach a certain size. Similarly, if your wealth is accumulating interest, logarithms can be used to ask how long it will take until you have a certain amount of wealth.
2. Logarithms also give us tools for measuring the runtime (or memory usage) of algorithms. When an algorithm uses a [divide_and_conquer divide and conquer] approach, the amount of time (or memory) used by the algorithm increases logarithmically as the input size grows linearly. For example, the amount of time that it takes to perform a [binary_search binary search] through $n$ possibilities is $\log_2(n),$ which means that the search takes one unit longer to run every time the set of things to search through doubles in size.
3. Logarithms give us tools for studying the tools we use to represent numbers. For example, humans tend to use ten different digits to represent numbers, while computers tend to use two digits (0 or 1) to represent numbers. Are some representations better or worse than others? What are the pros and cons of using more or fewer digits? For more on these ideas, see the page on [number_base number bases].
4. The human brain encodes various perceptions logarithmically. For example, the perceived tone of a sound goes up by one octave every time the frequency of air vibrations doubles. Your perception of tone is proportional to the logarithm (base 2) of the frequency. See also [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hick%27s_law Hick's law].

[fixme: 1. Logarithms give us tools for measuring the complexity of an object. For example, just as logarithms can be used to measure the length of a number (for a certain specific notion of "length"), logarithms can be used to measure the length of a computer program, and the length of the shortest program that can produce a certain output is one of the basic measures of "complexity." For more on this idea, refer to the page on [5v Kolmogorov complexity.]

[fixme: Logarithms are used to measure things that are exponentially distributed. For example, the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richter_magnitude_scale Richter scale measures the size of an earthquake]
